# Greater-than sign

From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia

Jump to: navigation, search

For the use of the ">" sign as punctuation, see [Bracket § Angle
brackets](/wiki/Bracket#Angle_brackets "Bracket").

[![](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/0d/Greater_than_sign.png)](/wiki/File:Greater_than_sign.png)

[](/wiki/File:Greater_than_sign.png "Enlarge")

Greater-than sign

The **greater-than sign** is a mathematical symbol that denotes an
[inequality](/wiki/Inequality_\(mathematics\) "Inequality \(mathematics\)")
between two values. The widely adopted form of two equal-length strokes
connecting in an [acute angle](/wiki/Acute_angle "Acute angle") at the right,
**>** , has been found in documents dated as far back as the 1560s. In typical
mathematical usage, the greater-than sign is typically placed between the two
values being compared and signals that the first number is greater than the
second number. Examples of typical usage include _1½ > 1_ and _1 > −2_. Since
the development of computer [programming languages](/wiki/Programming_language
"Programming language"), the greater-than sign and the [less-than
sign](/wiki/Less-than_sign "Less-than sign") have been repurposed for a range
of uses and operations.

## History[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Greater-than_sign&action=edit&section=1
"Edit section: History")]

The symbols < and > first appear in _Artis Analyticae Praxis ad Aequationes
Algebraicas Resolvendas_ (_The Analytical Arts Applied to Solving Algebraic
Equations_) by [Thomas Harriot](/wiki/Thomas_Harriot "Thomas Harriot")
(1560–1621), which was published posthumously in 1631. The text states:
"_Signum majoritatis ut_ a > b _significet_ a _majorem quam_ b" and "_Signum
minoritatis ut_ a < b _significet_ a _minorem quam_ b."

According to historian Art Johnson (page 144), while Harriot was surveying
North America, he saw a [Native
American](/wiki/Native_Americans_in_the_United_States "Native Americans in the
United States") with a symbol that resembled the greater-than sign both
backwards and forwards ( > and < ).[1] Johnson says it is likely he developed
the two symbols from this symbol.[1]

## Computing[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Greater-than_sign&action=edit&section=2
"Edit section: Computing")]

The **greater-than sign** (`>`) is an original [ASCII](/wiki/ASCII "ASCII")
character (hex 3E, decimal 62).

The [character](/wiki/Character_\(computing\) "Character \(computing\)") in
[Unicode](/wiki/Unicode "Unicode") is U+003E > GREATER-THAN SIGN (HTML `>`
**·** `>`); this is inherited from the same value in [ASCII](/wiki/ASCII
"ASCII").

Apart from this, Unicode also has the following variants:

  * U+232A 〉 RIGHT-POINTING ANGLE BRACKET (HTML `〉` **·** `⟩`)

### Angle brackets[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Greater-
than_sign&action=edit&section=3 "Edit section: Angle brackets")]

The greater-than sign is used for an approximation of the closing [angle
bracket](/wiki/Bracket#Angle_brackets "Bracket") (⟩). ASCII does not have
angular brackets.

### Programming language[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Greater-
than_sign&action=edit&section=4 "Edit section: Programming language")]

[BASIC](/wiki/BASIC "BASIC") and [C](/wiki/C_\(programming_language\) "C
\(programming language\)")-family languages, (including
[Java](/wiki/Java_\(programming_language\) "Java \(programming language\)")
and [C++](/wiki/C%2B%2B "C++")) use the operator `>` to mean "greater than".
In [Lisp](/wiki/Lisp_\(programming_language\) "Lisp \(programming
language\)")-family languages, `>` is a function used to mean "greater than".
In [Coldfusion](/wiki/Coldfusion "Coldfusion") and [Fortran](/wiki/Fortran
"Fortran"), operator `.GT.` means "greater than".

### Double greater-than sign[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Greater-
than_sign&action=edit&section=5 "Edit section: Double greater-than sign")]

The double greater-than sign (`>>`) is used for an approximation of the much
greater than sign (≫). ASCII does not have the much greater-than sign.

The double greater-than sign (`>>`) is also used for an approximation of the
closing [guillemet](/wiki/Guillemets "Guillemets") (»).

In [Java](/wiki/Java_\(programming_language\) "Java \(programming
language\)"), [C](/wiki/C_\(programming_language\) "C \(programming
language\)"), and [C++](/wiki/C%2B%2B "C++"), the operator `>>` is the [right-
shift operator](/wiki/Right-shift_operator "Right-shift operator"). In C++ it
is also used to get input from a [stream](/wiki/Stream_\(computing\) "Stream
\(computing\)"), similar to the C functions `getchar` and `fgets`.

In [Haskell](/wiki/Haskell_\(programming_language\) "Haskell \(programming
language\)"), the `>>` function is a monadic operator. It is used for
sequentially composing two actions, discarding any value produced by the
first. In that regard, it is like the statement sequencing operator in
imperative languages, such as the semicolon in C.

### Triple greater-than sign[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Greater-
than_sign&action=edit&section=6 "Edit section: Triple greater-than sign")]

The triple greater-than sign (>>>) is the unsigned right shift operator in
[JavaScript](/wiki/JavaScript "JavaScript"), and is the default
[Python](/wiki/Python_\(programming_language\) "Python \(programming
language\)") prompt of the interactive shell, often seen for code examples
which can be executed interactively in the interpreter

    
    
    ~:$ python
    Python 2.7.5 (default, Mar  9 2014, 22:15:05) 
    [GCC 4.2.1 Compatible Apple LLVM 5.0 (clang-500.0.68)] on darwin
    Type "help", "copyright", "credits" or "license" for more information.
    >>> print("Hello World")
    Hello World
    >>>
    

### Greater-than sign with equals sign[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Greater-
than_sign&action=edit&section=7 "Edit section: Greater-than sign with equals
sign")]

The greater-than sign plus the equals sign (`>=`) is used for an approximation
of the [greater than or equal to](/wiki/Greater_than_or_equal_to "Greater than
or equal to") sign (≥, the opposite of ≤). ASCII doesn't have a greater-than-
or-equal-to sign.

In [BASIC](/wiki/BASIC "BASIC"), [Lisp](/wiki/Lisp_\(programming_language\)
"Lisp \(programming language\)")-family languages, and
[C](/wiki/C_\(programming_language\) "C \(programming language\)")-family
languages (including [Java](/wiki/Java_\(programming_language\) "Java
\(programming language\)") and [C++](/wiki/C%2B%2B "C++")), operator `>=`
means "greater than or equal to". In [Sinclair BASIC](/wiki/Sinclair_BASIC
"Sinclair BASIC") it is encoded as a single-byte code point token.

In [Fortran](/wiki/Fortran "Fortran"), operator `.GE.` means "greater than or
equal to".

In [Bourne shell](/wiki/Bourne_shell "Bourne shell") and [Windows
PowerShell](/wiki/Windows_PowerShell "Windows PowerShell"), the operator `-ge`
means "greater than or equal to".

### Hyphen-minus with greater-than sign[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Greater-
than_sign&action=edit&section=8 "Edit section: Hyphen-minus with greater-than
sign")]

In some programming languages (for example
[F#](/wiki/F_Sharp_\(programming_language\) "F Sharp \(programming
language\)")), the greater-than sign is used in conjunction with a [hyphen-
minus](/wiki/Hyphen-minus "Hyphen-minus") to create an arrow (`->`). Arrows
like these could also be used in text where other [arrow
symbols](/wiki/Arrow_\(symbol\) "Arrow \(symbol\)") are unavailable. In the R
programming language, this can be used as the right assignment operator. In
the C, C++, and C# programming languages, this is used as a member access
operator.

### Shell scripts[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Greater-
than_sign&action=edit&section=9 "Edit section: Shell scripts")]

In [Bourne shell](/wiki/Bourne_shell "Bourne shell") (and many other shells),
greater-than sign is used to [redirect](/wiki/Redirection_\(Unix\)
"Redirection \(Unix\)") output to a file. Greater-than plus ampersand (`>&`)
is used to redirect to a [file descriptor](/wiki/File_descriptor "File
descriptor").

### Spaceship operator[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Greater-
than_sign&action=edit&section=10 "Edit section: Spaceship operator")]

Greater-than sign is used in the [spaceship operator](/wiki/Spaceship_operator
"Spaceship operator").

### HTML[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Greater-than_sign&action=edit&section=11
"Edit section: HTML")]

In [HTML](/wiki/HTML "HTML") (and [SGML](/wiki/SGML "SGML") and
[XML](/wiki/XML "XML")), the greater-than sign is used at the end of tags. The
greater-than sign may be included with `>`, while `≥` produces the
greater-than or equal to sign.

### E-mail and the Internet[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Greater-
than_sign&action=edit&section=12 "Edit section: E-mail and the Internet")]

The greater-than sign is used to denote [quotations](/wiki/Quotation
"Quotation") in the [e-mail](/wiki/E-mail "E-mail") and
[newsgroup](/wiki/Newsgroup "Newsgroup") formats, and this has been taken into
use also in forums. It is also used before a sentence for a sense of
implication. (>implying)
